\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Last week, we learned that random sampling is the most reliable way we know of obtaining data about populations without misleading biases. We also learned that it's far from perfect. Whenever we use data from a sample to estimate a population quantity, there will always be an error due to sampling. This week, we'll learn how to put an interval around our estimates to allow for sampling error. These intervals are called confidence intervals. Do you remember this animation of samples from the Census At School database? The question was about mode of travel to school. We can see considerable movement in the percentages from sample to sample.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
