\cf2 Skip to 2 minutes and 20 seconds\cb1 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 But to do it, we need to know "What's the margin of error we need to allow for". We used this slide in the last video of week five. The margins of error we need to allow for get smaller as the samples get larger. But it shouldn't be surprising that more information tends to get us closer to the truth. Percentages taken from samples as small as 30 can have enormous errors. The errors are much smaller if we have larger samples, like 1,000 (roughly 3 percentage points in the pictures we're seeing here). Here is sampling error displayed in a few more situations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508387#"}}{\fldrslt 
